===Etymology===
[[File:Armistice celebration. Yanks and Tommies., 11-1918 - NARA - 530789.tif|thumb|A [[celebration]] of the armistice on in 11 November 1918 that marked the end of [[World War I]]]]

From {{der|en|ML.|armistitium}}, from {{der|en|la|arma||arms, weapons}} + {{m|la|sistēre}} (from {{m|la|sistō||to halt, stand still}}, ultimately from {{der|en|ine-pro|*steh₂-||to stand up}}) + {{m|la|-ium||''suffix forming abstract nouns''}}. The word is cognate with from {{cog|fr|armistice}}.<ref>{{R:OED Online|part of speech=n|id=10864|date=June 2014}}</ref>

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/ˈɑmɪstɪs/|lang=en}}
* {{a|GA}} {{IPA|/ˈɑɹmɪstɪs/|/-məstəs/|lang=en}}
* {{hyphenation|ar|mis|tice|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A ([[short#Adjective|short]]) [[cessation] of [[combat#Noun|combat]]; a [[ceasefire]], a [[truce]]. {{defdate|from late 17th c.}}
# A [[formal]] [[agreement]], especially between [[nation]]s, to [[end#Verb|end]] combat.
# ''In the form'' '''{{l|en|Armistice}}''': {{short for|Armistice Day||[[November]] 11, the [[anniversary]] of the [[signing#Noun|signing]] of the armistice agreement to end [[World War I]], [[commemorate|commemorating]] the [[fall]]en of that War}}

